The first symbol of the string is t53.  
Within the grammar the only production that can yield t53 is the
terminal rule  

  NT6 → 't53'.

Consequently, in every derivation the non-terminal NT6 must produce
exactly this single token; it cannot produce any further symbols,
because every binary rule that begins with NT6 puts some other
non-terminal (NT4, NT5, NT8 …) in front of the t53, which would move the
t53 away from the first position.  
Therefore the start production

  S → NT6 NT5

is forced to split the string after the first token:

  NT6 ⇒ t53  and  NT5 ⇒ t35 t40 … t32   (25 tokens).

Now look at the possibilities for NT5.  
NT5 has only three binary rules

  NT5 → NT2 NT1   NT5 → NT9 NT8   NT5 → NT2 NT3

(and a few single–terminal rules that cannot apply because the second
token is t35, not one of NT5’s terminals).

So NT5 must use one of those three binary rules and its left child has
to start with the second token t35.

1. NT5 → NT9 NT8  
  NT9 can begin with t35 (terminal rule NT9→'t35'), but then NT9
  produces exactly one token, leaving NT8 to start with t40.  
  However every rule of NT8 begins with NT0 or NT9, and neither of them
  can generate t40 in first position.  Hence this branch fails.

2. NT5 → NT2 NT1  
  For NT2 to begin with t35, it must expand via NT2→NT3 … with
  NT3→'t35'.  The next symbol t40 would then have to be the first token
  of NT1.  Yet no derivation of NT1 can start with t40 (its first
  symbol is always generated by NT7, NT8 or NT6, none of which can
  produce t40 in first position).  This branch fails as well.

3. NT5 → NT2 NT3  
  Exactly the same difficulty occurs: after NT2 has produced the
  leading t35, the right component NT3 would have to start with t40.
  But every rule for NT3 begins with NT9, NT1 or NT3 itself; none of
  those non-terminals can generate t40 as their first token.  Hence this
  branch also fails.

Since every possible expansion for NT5 leads to an immediate
contradiction with the required second token of the string, NT5 cannot
generate the 25-token suffix.  Because NT5 cannot do so, S cannot
generate the whole string.

Therefore the given grammar does not generate the string.
